			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">Shamans do have an aggro reducer its an aa that roots the npc in place, knocks it back then lowers them on the hate list to the lowest amount. Its useable every 2-3 mins If I remember correctly and has low resist rates.
<br />

<br />
Chanters also do the highest dps out of any class, have debuffs and guess what they have 3 lines of aggro reducing spells: mem blur, Mez and the pop spell that lowers aggro without getting rid of it.
<br />

<br />
From the responces I hear some of you guys must not be in a heavy raiding guild that raids high end npcs. When an npc hits for 1200dmg + and quads you dont have enough time too tank the npc and hope your pet gets aggro off of you. 
<br />

<br />
All the above choices above classes you guys have talked about above do have a choice in whether or not how they control thier aggro with the exception of Chanter, Shaman and Beastlord. Be it wizard, ranger, rogue or whoever else they have the ability to start out slow and then speed up the dmg as the fight progresses therefore they dont particularly need a spell like concussion. While a debuffer on the other hand you have to start out with your most hate generating ability from the start.
<br />

<br />
Sure I imagine you could wait 30 seconds. But in a raid situation that 30 first seconds is the deciding factor in whether or not the raid succeeds or fails. In those 30 seconds of the npc not being slowed generally the main tank is killed along with at least 2 healers that heal the main tank due too the npc not being debuffed fast enough. So it basically comes down too debuffing the npc as quick as possible and praying that the main tank has enough aggro on the npc so that it wont come after you.
<br />

<br />
Two ideas for hate reduction that I like would be either give beastlords a self only proc spell that lowers hate with each proc. Or edit the beastlord slows so that they only give 1 disease counter kind of like the epic so that the slow generates very little aggro.</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
			</tr>
		</table></td>
