			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody"></span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>celodar wrote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Warriors have discs, paladins have divine aura, rangers have jolt, bards have a number of songs, rogues have evade/escape, monks just keel over, SK's keel over and smell funny or harmshield</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
Of the things you mentioned, only jolt, evade, and FD lower aggro. DA / harmshield is just invul (I suppose if you want to count 18 seconds of lack of aggro producing an aggro reducer okay), no warrior disc lowers their aggro, and no bard song lowers their aggro (that I am aware of) short of Fade which is a 100% mem wipe.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>SorrowsEnd wrote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">If we are wishing I'll go for an agro INCREASING spell. 
<br />

<br />
Just for that extra boost when I'm tanking and have a crying shadowknight or paladin in the group trying to outaunt me.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
Flash of Light is your friend. I almost never use Incap when I'm tanking. I would have to have VoQ, 9, SD (obviously), bard song, and not be slowing. Otherwise the number of mobs we pull I'm be oom once you include a fero every 2 minutes.
<br />

<br />
Some people don't like FoL because it can fear mobs. I say hogwash. On inc I assist the puller (a button totally devoted for /ass XXX.. makes it nice and fast, in addition to my generic assist button), and as soon as the mob is in range I'm already casting Revenge. Once mob is attacking me and I do 2-3 rounds of melee while spells refresh I hit Fol once then twice. If some out of range jackass pulls aggro off you THEN.. it isn't your fault that the mob went running, plain and simple.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Ssorraak wrote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Shamans do have an aggro reducer its an aa that roots the npc in place, knocks it back then lowers them on the hate list to the lowest amount. Its useable every 2-3 mins If I remember correctly and has low resist rates.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
You are referring to: <a href="http://lucy.allakhazam.com/spelllist.html?searchtext=Virulent+Paralysis" target="_blank" class="postlink">these spells</a> which do not lower aggro at all, and in fact raise it. It's a CC tool, not an aggro device. Not to mention rooted mobs toss all conventional aggro rules out the window.
<br />

<br />
----
<br />

<br />
But in response to the actual idea, a weak weak form of Boggle would actually be balanced in AA form. A 0.5 cast time spell with 45 second refresh that lowers our hate by 200. I can't say it would be the most useful thing ever but anything more and our superior ability to be a group slower is even further increased.
<br />

<br />
But I have to agree with the general consensus that it isn't that much needed. If you find you are drawing aggro just from melee plus a couple nukes (if you are dot heavy, that's part of the problem) then you need to have a pep talk with your tank. Or if he's a warrior, forgive him, cast FoL a couple times, and tell him to hit the back of the mob cuz you're tanking from now on. <img src="images/smiles/icon_wink.gif" alt="Wink" border="0" /></span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
			</tr>
		</table></td>
